High 81F. Winds WSW at 5 to 10 mph.. Some clouds. Low around 60F. Winds SW at 5 to 10 mph. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 11:38 am Sports Director A roadway treated with Milliken\'s Liquitint Winter DelDOT is out pre-treating roadways ahead of Friday night\'s projected snowstorm, but things might look a little different this time. DelDOT\'s C.R. McLeod said they are experimenting mixing in some color with the white-grey brining solution that is put down to try to lower the freezing temperature on the roadways and avoid ice. "It\'s actually going to be very easy to identify when you see this turquoise-blue tint that\'s been applied to the road surfaces." The product is Liquitint Winter, made by textile and chemical country Miliken, and you may have seen it on the roads in other states, and even if you\'ve been through a car wash and wondered why the water was blue. "It\'s deemed to be environmentally friendly, it\'s water-soluble, so it\'s not going to stain the road, it\'s not going to damage cars." Liquitint is available in a rainbow of colors, but McLeod said blue has a purpose outside of simply not being white. "Darker colors absorb more sunlight, so as we\'re dealing with storms, having something that\'s a little darker in color can only help enhance that melting effect we\'re trying to achieve." According to Miliken, Liquitint is non-staining and has a limited opportunity for skin exposure. McLeod said they have already tested Liquitint in parts of Sussex County during previous snows this season, but they are looking forward to seeing how it works with the brine during this storm. If successful, McLeod said they could consider using it with rock salt in the future as the storm gets underway.
